06907nam a22008295i 9780271083148DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710831487 a10.1515/97802710831482doi  a(DE-B1597)584315  a(OCoLC)1262307276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX5199.J4bD44 2018eb 7aREL0030002bisacsh04a283.09222300aDefending the Faith :bJohn Jewel and the Elizabethan Church /ced. by Angela Ranson, André A. Gazal, Sarah Bastow. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: John Jewel and the Invention of the Church of England -- t1 John Jewel's Early Life: Developing a Community of Reformers -- tPart I: John Jewel as Theologian, Polemicist, and Apologist -- t2 The Homiletical Theologian: Jewel's Self- Identity as Preacher of the Word -- t3 John Jewel at Paul's Cross: A Culture of Persuasion and England's Emerging Public Sphere -- t4 "Silence Is a Fine Jewel for a Woman": Anne Cooke Bacon, Jewel's Apology, and Reformed Women's Publications -- t5 "A Crime So Heinous": The Concept of Heresy in John Jewel's Apology of the Church of England -- t6 An Apology of the Church of England's Cathedrals -- t7 The Jewel-Harding Controversy: Defending the Champion -- t8 Defending the Defender of the Faith: The Use of History in Responses to Queen Elizabeth's Excommunication -- tPart II: The Impact and Legacy of John Jewel -- t9 Moses the Magistrate: The Mosaic Theological Imaginaries of John Jewel and Richard Hooker in Elizabethan Apologetics -- t10 The Use and Abuse of John Jewel in Richard Hooker's Defense of the English Church -- t11 Redefining Unity in the Jacobean Church: The Legacy of John Jewel -- t12 Edwin Sandys and the Defense of the Faith -- t13 Defense, Dialectic, and Dialogue: The Role of the Antagonist in the English Church -- t14 A Multifaceted Jewel: English Episcopacy, Ignatian Authenticity, and the Rise of Critical Patristic Scholarship -- t15 Defending Reformation Anglicanism: The Bishop Jewel Society at Oxford University, 1947-1975 -- tAppendix: The Publications of the Jewel-Harding Controversy, 1560-1640 -- tSelected Bibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume brings together a diverse group of Reformation scholars to examine the life, work, and enduring significance of John Jewel, Bishop of Salisbury from 1560 to 1571.A theologian and scholar who worked with early reformers in England such as Peter Martyr Vermigli, Martin Bucer, and Thomas Cranmer, Jewel had a long-lasting influence over religious culture and identity. The essays included in this book shed light on often-neglected aspects of Jewel's work, as well as his standing in Elizabethan culture not only as a priest but as a leader whose work as a polemicist and apologist played an important role in establishing the authority and legitimacy of the Elizabethan Church of England. The contributors also place Jewel in the wider context of gender studies, material culture, and social history. With its inclusion of a short biography of Jewel's early life and a complete list of his works published between 1560 and 1640, Defending the Faith is a fresh and robust look at an important Reformation figure who was recognized as a champion of the English Church, both by his enemies and by his fellow reformers.In addition to the editors, contributors to this volume are Andrew Atherstone, Ian Atherton, Paul Dominiak, Alice Ferron, Paul A. Hartog, Torrance Kirby, W. Bradford Littlejohn, Aislinn Muller, Joshua Rodda, and Lucy Wooding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; t